---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import LineageContextBanner from '../../components/LineageContextBanner.tsx';
import Claim from '../../components/Claim.astro';
import FactTier from '../../components/FactTier.astro';
import AncestorPractices from '../../components/viz/AncestorPractices.tsx';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Ancestor Practices — What Vellala Actually Did — Decoded"
  description="A material-practice tour of Kongu Vellala ancestry: crops, tools, governance roles, and memorial markers — each tier-tagged with tradition framing vs. evidence framing."
>
  <main id="main-content" class="mx-auto max-w-5xl px-6 py-12 sm:py-16">
    <LineageContextBanner client:load />
    <nav class="mb-8 text-sm text-stone-500">
      <a href="/" class="hover:text-stone-900">Home</a>
      <span class="mx-2" aria-hidden="true">/</span>
      <a href="/lineage" class="hover:text-stone-900">Lineage</a>
      <span class="mx-2" aria-hidden="true">/</span>
      <span class="text-stone-700">Ancestor Practices</span>
    </nav>

    {/* Hero */}
    <header class="mb-10">
      <p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-emerald-700">
        Material practice · செயல்பாடு
      </p>
      <h1 class="mt-2 text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight sm:text-5xl">
        <span class="block">Ancestor Practices</span>
        <span class="mt-2 block font-tamil text-3xl font-medium text-stone-700 sm:text-4xl">
          முன்னோர் செய்தவை
        </span>
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-4 max-w-2xl text-base text-stone-600 sm:text-lg">
        What did Vellala ancestors actually <em>do</em>? Not the romantic "noble cultivator" story, not the
        shame-only "feudal oppressor" story — the concrete material practice: which crops they grew, which
        tools they used, which offices they held, and how they remembered their dead.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-3 max-w-2xl text-base text-stone-600 sm:text-lg">
        Each hotspot below is tagged with an evidence tier. Tradition framing and evidence framing are shown
        side by side so the gaps between them are visible.
      </p>
    </header>

    {/* The interactive */}
    <section class="mb-12">
      <AncestorPractices client:visible />
    </section>

    {/* Defensible claims */}
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight">
        The most defensible statements
        <span class="ml-2 font-tamil text-xl font-medium text-stone-600">உறுதியான கூற்றுகள்</span>
      </h2>
      <p class="mt-2 max-w-2xl text-stone-600">
        Of everything above, these are the pieces with the strongest documentary support.
      </p>
      <div class="prose prose-stone mt-4 max-w-none text-stone-800 sm:text-lg">
        <p>
          <Claim tier="green" sources={["vellala-tank-irrigation"]}>
            Kongu Vellala communities historically specialised in tank-fed (ஏரி) and well-fed (கமலை) irrigation in the semi-arid Kongu region, supporting paddy, cotton, sugarcane, and millet cultivation.
          </Claim>
          The hydraulic infrastructure — earthen tank bunds, sluice gates, command-area channels, leather-bag well lifts — is the most concretely preserved part of this legacy, attested in landscape and inscription alike.
        </p>
        <p>
          <Claim tier="green" sources={["kongu-region-buffer"]}>
            The Kongu region historically functioned as a buffer zone between the Chola, Pandya, and Chera kingdoms,
          </Claim>
          which is why the agrarian economy here developed its own distinct profile — drier than the Cauvery delta,
          more cotton-and-millet than rice — and produced its own clan structure and titles.
        </p>
        <p>
          <Claim tier="yellow" sources={["naadu-kal-hero-stones"]}>
            Nadukal (நடுகல், hero stones) commemorating warriors who died defending cattle, land, or kin are densely attested across Kongu Nadu and form one of the oldest continuous Tamil memorial traditions.
          </Claim>
          The practice itself is green-tier well-attested; attribution of specific stones to named ancestors is community-internal and rarely independently corroborated.
        </p>
        <p>
          <Claim tier="yellow" sources={["vellala-kaveri-origin"]}>
            The Vellala cluster is most commonly hypothesised to have originated as elite land-owning cultivators of the Kaveri delta and other wet-rice zones during and after the Sangam era, expanding subsequently into Kongu, Tondai, and Pandya country.
          </Claim>
          The hypothesis is plausible and widely cited; the Sangam-Velir-to-modern-Vellala line of descent specifically is debated and not securely demonstrated.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    {/* Honest caveat */}
    <section class="mb-12 rounded-2xl border border-amber-200 bg-amber-50 p-6">
      <h2 class="flex items-center gap-2 text-xl font-semibold text-amber-900">
        What this page is not saying
        <FactTier tier="yellow" />
      </h2>
      <div class="prose prose-stone mt-3 max-w-none text-stone-800">
        <p>
          Showing the tools, the crops, and the offices does not establish that the Vellala were uniquely
          virtuous, or that the rural labour economy was egalitarian. The same tank that irrigated the
          fields was dug and maintained by labouring castes; the same threshing floor that processed the
          year's grain was the site at which crop shares were distributed unequally; the same Naattaanmai
          who arbitrated kootam marriages also enforced caste-based marriage and labour rules.
        </p>
        <p>
          The point is the inverse of romanticisation: <em>and</em> the inverse of pure shame. The
          ancestors farmed, irrigated, governed, and remembered their dead. They also operated inside —
          and helped maintain — a stratified agrarian order. Both are true; this page tries to show both.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    {/* Cross-links */}
    <section class="rounded-2xl border border-stone-200 bg-white p-6">
      <h2 class="text-base font-semibold text-stone-900">Connected pages</h2>
      <ul class="mt-3 grid gap-3 sm:grid-cols-3">
        <li>
          <a href="/lineage/vellala" class="block rounded-xl border border-stone-200 px-4 py-3 hover:border-emerald-300 hover:bg-emerald-50">
            <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wide text-stone-500">Caste cluster</p>
            <p class="font-medium text-stone-900">Vellala (வேளாளர்)</p>
            <p class="mt-1 text-xs text-stone-600">Etymology, sub-groups, contested historiography.</p>
          </a>
        </li>
        <li>
          <a href="/lineage/kongu" class="block rounded-xl border border-stone-200 px-4 py-3 hover:border-amber-300 hover:bg-amber-50">
            <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wide text-stone-500">Region</p>
            <p class="font-medium text-stone-900">Kongu Nadu (கொங்கு நாடு)</p>
            <p class="mt-1 text-xs text-stone-600">The semi-arid western Tamil plateau.</p>
          </a>
        </li>
        <li>
          <a href="/lineage/gounder" class="block rounded-xl border border-stone-200 px-4 py-3 hover:border-sky-300 hover:bg-sky-50">
            <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wide text-stone-500">Title</p>
            <p class="font-medium text-stone-900">Gounder (கவுண்டர்)</p>
            <p class="mt-1 text-xs text-stone-600">The headman title used by Kongu Vellala.</p>
          </a>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <p class="mt-5 text-sm">
        <a href="/lineage" class="font-medium text-emerald-700 hover:underline">← Back to Lineage</a>
      </p>
    </section>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>
